**Full Text (summary, not verbatim)**:
Melissa Perri argues that many organizations mistakenly believe their AI strategy is flawed when they see poor results or slow progress. In reality, the core issue is often not the strategy itself, but how it is interpreted and implemented across different levels of the organization. Leadership may define ambitious AI goals, but those ideas frequently fail to translate into clear product requirements, engineering execution, or operational workflows. This creates a gap where teams are technically “aligned” on paper but not in practice. The post highlights that successful execution requires a strong translation layer — ensuring that high-level strategy is broken down into actionable decisions, clear priorities, and concrete behaviors for teams. Without this, even strong strategies fail in execution because they never fully make it out of abstract planning into real systems of work.

